  "introduction": "Imagine a giant Lego castle. If you zoom in close enough to see just one single brick, that's like looking at a cell! Today, we are going to be microscopic detectives. We will meet Robert Hooke, the man who first saw these 'bricks' of life back in 1665, and learn how they build everything from bacteria to blue whales.",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "The session covers the discovery of cells by Robert Hooke, the classification into prokaryotic (no nucleus) and eukaryotic (true nucleus), and a detailed look at the cell envelope (membrane, wall, cytoplasm) and the nucleus.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Cells are the basic unit of life; discovered by Robert Hooke in cork.",
      "Prokaryotes lack a nuclear membrane; Eukaryotes have one.",
      "The cell envelope includes the plasma membrane (selectively permeable), cell wall (plants only), and cytoplasm."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "Cells are the fundamental units of life. Robert Hooke observed dead cork cells in 1665, coining the term 'cell'. Cells are broadly classified into Prokaryotic (e.g., bacteria) which lack a defined nucleus, and Eukaryotic (plants/animals) which possess a true nucleus enclosed by a nuclear membrane. The cell envelope consists of the plasma membrane (a flexible boundary that regulates transport), the cytoplasm (the fluid matrix containing organelles), and in plants only, a rigid cell wall made of cellulose. Inside eukaryotes lies the Nucleus, the control center housing chromosomes (DNA) and nucleolus."
  },
